  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Oliver Johnson has recieved notes from Harriet Martineau that refer to some &quot;step she has felt it incumbent on her to take.&quot; (The meaning of this is unclear.) Johnson goes on to say: &quot;I take it for granted the Committee cannot be so unwise as to discontinue her correspondence just at the moment when we are about to reap its fruits. I have a petty letter from Howland, for this week&apos;s paper.&quot; He discusses the &quot;follies of Pillsbury and Foster&quot; and Wendell Phillips&apos;s mistaken attempt to cover them. Oliver Johnson explains his editorial attitude toward Foster. He thanks Maria Weston Chapman for the poems of Mrs. [Maria Gowen?] Brooks.</subfield>
